ce:section.ce:para:
The relation between the fluorescence quenching efficiency of Tg N,P-CDs and the concentration of 2,4-DNP or 4-NP was investigated under the optimal experimental conditions. The PL intensity of Tg N,P-CDs decreases with the increase in the concentration of 2,4-DNP or 4-NP (Fig. 8
                        a -8b). PL intensity ratio of Tg N,P-CDs is linear with the concentration of 2,4-DNP (0–50 μM, R2 = 0.9923) (Fig. 8c) and 4-NP concentration (0–50 μM, R2 = 0.9926) (Fig. 8d), and the detection limits of 2,4-DNP and 4-NP are 35.09 nM and 78.62 nM respectively, and the S/N is 3 (Table 1
                        ). It is well known that 2,4-DNP pollution is very serious, and at present study on 2,4-DNP mainly focuses on the adsorption and removal of 2,4-DNP [1,25]. The reports on the detection of 2,4-DNP by CDs are relatively few, but it is very important for 2,4-DNP and 4-NP analysis.

The fluorescent nanoprobes Tg N,P-CDs were used to detect 2,4-DNP and 4-NP in real tap water, river water, waste water and soil samples. The recovery experiments were carried out by the standard addition method. The good percentage recoveries and relative standard deviation (%RSD) were obtained through analysis. For water samples, the recoveries of 2,4-DNP and 4-NP were estimated to fall within 94–105.03% and 96.60–105.66%, respectively (Table 2
                        ); For soil samples, the recoveries of 2,4-DNP and 4-NP were estimated to fall within 92.30–97.20% and 94.60–97.00%, respectively (Table 3
                        ), presenting the sensibility of Tg N,P-CDs on 2,4-DNP and 4-NP in tap water, river water, waste water, parking lot soil, road soil and industry zone soil (n = 3). Therefore, they are easy, sensitive and fast to detect 2,4-DNP and 4-NP in real water and soil.
